# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to find the sum of all root-to-leaf paths in the binary tree, where each root-to-leaf path represents a number. To do this, we can traverse the tree in a depth-first manner, keeping track of the current number formed by the path from the root to the current node. When we reach a leaf node, we add the current number to our running sum.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can use a recursive approach to traverse the tree. We start with the root node and a current number of 0. At each node, we multiply the current number by 10 and add the node's value to get the new current number. If the current node is a leaf node, we add the current number to our running sum. Otherwise, we recursively traverse the left and right subtrees, passing the new current number to each.



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
We visit each node exactly once, so the time complexity is $$O(n)$$, where n is the number of nodes in the tree.
- Space complexity:
The space complexity is $$O(h)$$, where h is the height of the tree, due to the recursive calls on the function call stack. In the worst case, the tree is a skewed tree with a height of n, resulting in a space complexity of $$O(n)$$. However, in the best case, the tree is a balanced tree with a height of log n, resulting in a space complexity of O(log n).



