I promise I did not read any other solutions when writing my code.
The Idea:
There is a function DFS, depth-first-search, and it does...
* If ```current == NULL``` return as you cannot do anything.
* If ```current->left == NULL && current->right == NULL``` there are no children. We will then do ```total += current->val```.
* Else, recurse ```DFS(current->left, value*10+current->val)``` and ```DFS(current->right, value*10+current->val)```.

Time Complexity --> O(N), N is the number nodes in the tree.
Space Complexity --> O(1).

**Test Run:**
```
Lets say the tree is:
			4
		  /   \
		9      0
	             \
				  1
DFS(4, 0) runs DFS(9, 4) + DFS(0, 4).
DFS(9, 4) adds 49 to total.
DFS(0, 4) adds runs DFS(NULL, 40) + DFS(1, 40).
DFS(NULL, 40) doesn't do anything.
DFS(1, 40) adds 401 to total.
In the total == 450.
```
**Note:** DFS is a void function.
```
class Solution {
public:

    //This is the output.
    int total = 0;

    void DFS(TreeNode* current, int value){
        //If current == NULL, return.
        if (current == NULL){
            return;
        }

        //If current has no children add value*10+current->val to total. Then return.
        if (current->left == NULL && current->right == NULL){
            total += current->val;
            total += value*10;
            return
        }

        //If not run DFS(current->left&right, (value*10)+current->val)
        DFS(current->left, (value*10)+current->val);
        DFS(current->right, (value*10)+current->val);  
    }

    int sumNumbers(TreeNode* root) {
        //Run DFS to change total.
        DFS(root, 0);
        //Return total.
        return total;
    }
};
```
