This is definitely O(1) space because we have defined the hash functions. In this case, n%10 can take 10 values, n%19 can take 19 values. So the total number of entries in the maps put together will only be a maximum of 29.

```
class Solution {
    Map<Integer, Integer> map1 = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();
    Map<Integer, Integer> map2 = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();

    int val1 = 10;
    int val2 = 19;

    public List<Integer> majorityElement(int[] nums) {
        Set<Integer> res = new HashSet<Integer>();
        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++) {
            put(nums[i]);
        }

        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++) {
            if(get(nums[i]) > nums.length/3) {
                res.add(nums[i]);
            }
        }

        return new ArrayList<Integer>(res);
    }

    private void put(int num) {
        map1.put(num%val1, map1.getOrDefault(num%val1, 0)+1);
        map2.put(num%val2, map2.getOrDefault(num%val2, 0)+1);
    }

    private int get(int num) {
        return Math.min(map1.get(num%val1), map2.get(num%val2));
    }
}
```

