# Approach
The key idea behind this algorithm is that in an array of size n, there can be at most two elements that appear more than ⌊ n/3 ⌋ times. By eliminating pairs of different elements, the algorithm identifies the potential majority elements, and then it verifies their actual frequencies to ensure they meet the threshold.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(2n) = O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> majorityElement(vector<int>& nums) {
        int cnt1 = 0, cnt2 = 0;
        int el1 = INT_MIN;
        int el2 = INT_MIN;
        int n = nums.size();
        for(int i = 0; i< n; i++){
            if(cnt1 == 0 && nums[i] != el2){
                cnt1 = 1;
                el1 = nums[i];
            }
            else if(cnt2 == 0 && nums[i] != el1){
                cnt2 = 1;
                el2 = nums[i];
            }
            else if(el1 == nums[i]) cnt1++;
            else if(el2 == nums[i]) cnt2++;
            else{
                cnt1--;
                cnt2--;
            }
        }
        vector<int> ans;
        cnt1 = 0, cnt2 = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i< n; i++){
            if(el1 == nums[i]) cnt1++;
            if(el2 == nums[i]) cnt2++;
        }
        int mini = (int)(n/3)+1;
        if(cnt1 >= mini) ans.push_back(el1);
        if(cnt2 >= mini) ans.push_back(el2);
        sort(ans.begin(), ans.end());
        return ans;
    }
};
```

