/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
// Boyer-Moore voting algorithm
// [Explanation] 
// The key of this prolem is understanding that [n/3] times eppearances,
// which means to find the majority for more than ceiling of [n/3], the answer would 
// be less than or equal to two numbers.
//
// The algorithm uses O(1) extra space and O(N) time. It requires exactly 2 passes 
// over the input list. It's also quite simple to implement, though a little trickier 
// to understand how it works.
// In the first pass, we generate 2 candidates' values which are the majority values 
// if there is a majority. The second pass simply counts the frequency of that values to 
// confirm. The first pass is the interesting part.
// In the first pass, we need 2 values:
//      (1) 2 candidates' value, initially set to any value.
//      (2) 2 counters, initially set to 0.
// For each element in our input list, we first examine the count value. If the count 
// is equal to 0, we set the candidate to the value at the current element. Next, first 
// compare the element's value to the current candidate value. If they are the same, we 
// increment count by 1. If they are different, we decrement count by 1.
/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> majorityElement(vector<int>& nums) {
        int count1 = 0, count2 = 0, candidate1 = nums[0], candidate2 = nums[0];

        // first iteration to find the candidates
        for (auto num : nums) {
            if (candidate1 == num) count1++;            // check the canididate before calculating the counter.
            else if (candidate2 == num) count2++;
            else if (count1 == 0) { candidate1 = num; count1 = 1; }
            else if (count2 == 0) { candidate2 = num; count2 = 1; }
            else { count1--; count2--; }
        }

        // second iteration to count the frequency of the candidates
        count1 = count2 = 0;
        for (auto num : nums) {
            if (candidate1 == num) count1++;
            // if (candidate2 != candidate1 && candidate2 == num) count2++;
            else if (candidate2 == num) count2++;
        }

        vector<int> result;
        if (count1 > nums.size() / 3) result.push_back(candidate1);
        if (count2 > nums.size() / 3) result.push_back(candidate2);      
        return result;
    }
};
```

