### Moore's voting algorithm for finding all majority elements

Time complexiy - O(n)
space complexity - O(1)

**Code**
```java
public static List<Integer> majorityElement(int[] nums) {
	List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

	Integer num1 = null, num2 = null;
	int c1 = 0, c2 = 0;

	for (int el : nums) {
		if (num1 != null && el == num1)
			c1++;
		else if (num2 != null && el == num2)
			c2++;
		else if (c1 == 0) {
			num1 = el;
			c1 = 1;
		} else if (c2 == 0) {
			num2 = el;
			c2 = 1;
		} else {
			c1--;
			c2--;
		}
	}

	int count = 0;
	for (int el : nums) {
		if (num1 != null && el == num1)
			count++;
	}
	if (count > nums.length / 3)
		list.add(num1);

	count = 0;
	for (int el : nums) {
		if (num2 != null && el == num2)
			count++;
	}
	if (count > nums.length / 3)
		list.add(num2);
	return list;
}
```

**Explanation**

The algorithm given above is based on some important details in the question, as in this question we are required to find all the elements that occur more than n/3 number of times, there can be only two majority elements.

so once we understand that there are only two majority elements, we initialise two integers of `Integer` class because the input also has negative numbers. Also initialise two count variables c1 and c2.

now iterate in the array and use the following logic:-
- if `num1 == el` then increment c1
- else if `num2 == el` then increment c2
- else if `c1==0` set a new value for num1 and increment the count of c1 to 1.
- else if `c2 == 0` set a new value for num1 and increment the count of c2 to 1.
- else if none of the above holds then decrement both c1 and c2.

