# Approach
1. If length of array is one, return the list containing the only number.
2. If length of array is two, add the first element to the list and check if the second number is equal or not. If it is not equal to the previous, add second element also to the list. Return the list.
3. Sort the Array
4. Initiaze an empty result list.
5. Iterate through the array (from second index to the length)

5.1 if the element is equal to the previous one, increase the    current count of the element. 

5.2 if the current count is greater than length/3, then add the list, and mark the current element as already added.

5.3 else(element is not equal to the previous one) -> prev will be initialized to the current element , and count to 1, and added will be false.

6. Return the result;

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n)$$ (assuming it used counting sort)
- Space complexity:
$$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> majorityElement(int[] nums) {
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<Integer>();
        result.clear();

        Arrays.sort(nums);
        int prev = nums[0];
        int n = nums.length;
        int count = 1;
        boolean added = false;
        if(n == 1){
            result.add(prev);
            return result;
        }
        if(n==2){
            result.add(prev);
            if(prev != nums[1]) {
            result.add(nums[1]);

            }
            return result;
        }
        for (int i=1; i<n; i++) {
            if (prev == nums[i]) {
                count++;

                if(count > n/3 && !added) {
                    result.add(prev);
                    added = true;
                }

            } else {
                prev = nums[i];
                count = 1;
                added = false;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

