Intution for the problem :

**Main pick of this problem is to under that once you move from cell i,j to cell l,m you can never reach the cell i,j.**

Let this sink in. 

Why above statement is true? SInce we are looking from an stricly increasing path, that means if we have moved from cell i,j to l,m that mean value at l,m is greater then value at i,j. So when we will be exploring l,m we wont pick i,j beacuse its value is less then l,m.


Rest of the code is plain dfs with along with that we are also storing intermidiate results.

```
class Solution {
    public int longestIncreasingPath(int[][] matrix) {
        if(matrix.length==0)
             return 0;

        int dp[][] = new int[matrix.length][matrix[0].length];

        int max = 0;

        for(int i=0;i<matrix.length;i++) {
            for(int j=0;j<matrix[0].length;j++) {
                int distance = dfs(i,j,dp,matrix);
                max = Math.max(distance,max);
            }
        }

        return max;
    }


    int dfs(int i,int j,int dp[][],int matrix[][]) {
        if(dp[i][j]!=0) {
            return dp[i][j];
        }else {
            int left=0,right=0,down=0,up=0;

            if(i-1>=0 && matrix[i-1][j] > matrix[i][j]) {
                up = 1 + dfs(i-1,j,dp,matrix);
            }
            if(i+1<matrix.length && matrix[i+1][j]>matrix[i][j]) {
                down = 1 + dfs(i+1,j,dp,matrix);
            }
            if(j-1>=0 && matrix[i][j-1] > matrix[i][j]) {
                left = 1 + dfs(i,j-1,dp,matrix);
            }
            if(j+1<matrix[0].length && matrix[i][j+1]>matrix[i][j]) {
                right = 1 + dfs(i,j+1,dp,matrix);
            }

            dp[i][j] = Math.max(1,Math.max(Math.max(left,right),Math.max(up,down)));
        }
      return dp[i][j];
    }
}
```

