* **LEVEL ORDER TRAVERSAL**

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> levelOrder(Node* root) {
        // it's just simple level order traversal, with just one change..
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        if(root == NULL)
            return res;

        queue<Node*> q;
        q.push(root);
        while(!q.empty()){

            int size = q.size();
            vector<int> sub_res;
            for(int i =0; i < size; ++i){
                Node* curr = q.front();   // get the front element of the queue or we can say, pop the orderwise(left to right) elements 
                q.pop();                  // of the particular level.. after getting the element push it into our sub_res array.... 

                sub_res.push_back(curr->val);

                for(auto &v : curr->children){  // THIS IS THE ONLY CHANGE OVER THE SIMPLE LEVEL ORDER TRAVERSAL.. BUT WHY? 
                    q.push(v);                  // Actually, after getting elements from the queue, we will push all of it's childrens into the queue..
                }
            }
            res.push_back(sub_res);             // atlast, push all the elements(or nodes) of the same level into our solution space..
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

**TIME COMPLEXITY : `O(N + E)`, where N :- total number of nodes in a N-ary tree & E :- total number of childrens one node has.. (like graphs).**
**SPACE COMPLEXITY :` O(N)`, (for using queue)**
